M. Chapter LX The Fourth Crusade . 
Part I. Schism Of The Greeks And Latins . 
Isaac Angelus Dethroned By His Brother Alexius . 
Origin Of The Fourth Crusade . 
Alliance Of The French And Venetians With The Son Of Isaac . 
Their Naval Expedition To Constantinople . 
The Two Sieges And Final Conquest Of The City By The Latins . 
The restoration of the Western empire by Charlemagne was speedily followed by the separation of the Greek and Latin churches . 
In the course of the present History , the aversion of the Greeks for the Latins has been often visible and conspicuous . 
Such were the crimes which provoked the zeal of the patriarchs of Constantinople and which were justified with equal zeal by the doctors of the Latin church . 
The Oriental patriarch continues to apply the images of thunder , earthquake , hail , wild boar , precursors of Antichrist , c . 
The mysterious subject of the procession of the Holy Ghost is discussed in the historical , theological , and controversial sense , or nonsense , by the Jesuit Petavius . 
Before the shrine of St . 
His language most clearly proves , that neither the filioque , nor the Athanasian creed were received at Rome about the year . 
The Missi of Charlemagne pressed him to declare , that all who rejected the filioque , or at least the doctrine , must be damned . 
With the aid of his court the Greek patriarch was victorious but in the furious contest he deposed in his turn the successor of St . 
Peter , and involved the Latin church in the reproach of heresy and schism . 
By a delusive promise of succor or reward , the popes were tempted to countenance these various proceedings and the synods of Constantinople were ratified by their epistles or legates . 
The darkness and corruption of the tenth century suspended the intercourse , without reconciling the minds , of the two nations . 
The rising majesty of Rome could no longer brook the insolence of a rebel and Michael Cerularius was excommunicated in the heart of Constantinople by the pope's legates . 
Shaking the dust from their feet , they deposited on the altar of St . 
The synod of Constantinople , held in the year , is the viiith of the general councils , the last assembly of the East which is recognized by the Roman church . 
She rejects the synods of Constantinople of the years and , which were , however , equally numerous and noisy but they were favorable to Photius . 
