In one respect I can indeed perceive the accidental operation of the crusades , not so much in producing a benefit as in removing an evil . 
This oppressive system was supported by the arts of the clergy and the swords of the barons . 
Among the causes that undermined that Gothic edifice , a conspicuous place must be allowed to the crusades . 
The estates of the barons were dissipated , and their race was often extinguished , in these costly and perilous expeditions . 
The conflagration which destroyed the tall and barren trees of the forest gave air and scope to the vegetation of the smaller and nutritive plants of the soil . 
On the consequences of the crusades , compare the valuable Essay of Reeren , that of M. Choiseul d'Aillecourt , and a chapter of Mr. Forster's Mahometanism Unveiled . 
I may admire this gentleman's learning and industry , without pledging myself to his wild theory of prophets interpretation . 
