Chapter LXV Elevation Of Timour Or Tamerlane , And His Death Part III . 
The marriage of six of the emperor's grandsons was esteemed an act of religion as well as of paternal tenderness and the pomp of the ancient caliphs was revived in their nuptials . 
They were celebrated in the gardens of Canighul , decorated with innumerable tents and pavilions , which displayed the luxury of a great city and the spoils of a victorious camp . 
