The siege of Constantinople by the Turks attracts our first attention to the person and character of the great destroyer . 
His first education and sentiments were those of a devout Mussulman and as often as he conversed with an infidel , he purified his hands and face by the legal rites of ablution . 
to brand the prophet of Mecca as a robber and impostor . 
The Persian might indeed contribute to his amusement , and the Arabic to his edification and such studies are familiar to the Oriental youth . 
But the influence of religion and learning were employed without effect on his savage and licentious nature . 
His sobriety is attested by the silence of the Turkish annals , which accuse three , and three only , of the Ottoman line of the vice of drunkenness . 
For the character of Mahomet II . 
it is dangerous to trust either the Turks or the Christians . 
