The improvements of Rome , since the fifteenth century , have not been the spontaneous produce of freedom and industry . 
A second and more artificial cause of the growth of a metropolis is the residence of a monarch , the expense of a luxurious court , and the tributes of dependent provinces . 
The beauty and splendor of the modern city may be ascribed to the abuses of the government , to the influence of superstition . 
has been marked by the rapid elevation of a new family , enriched by the childish pontiff at the expense of the church and country . 
Peter , the most glorious structure that ever has been applied to the use of religion . 
Peter's , is detained by a column of Egyptian granite , which rises between two lofty and perpetual fountains , to the height of one hundred and twenty feet . 
